benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: PUT /1.0/kb/accounts/{accountId}/paymentMethods/{paymentMethodId}/setDefault - Set the default payment method

covered: Valid Request scenarios (TC01, TC02, TC03, TC04, TC05) cover updating the default payment method with various parameter combinations.
Non-Existing Resource handling (TC08, TC09, TC10) covered for account, payment method existence and ownership.
Authorization / authentication scenarios (TC12) covered for unauthorized access; missing header (TC11) tested.
Error handling / service availability (TC13, TC18, TC19) covered for 503, 504/503 timeouts, and input validation on headers.
Input validation / UUID format handling (TC06, TC07, TC16, TC23) covered for invalid/malformed IDs and boundary UUID values.
Auditing / header usage (TC04) and pluginProperty handling (TC03, TC15, TC24) covered for header-driven auditing and plugin properties.
Performance/scale scenarios (TC17, TC22) covered for large numbers of unpaid invoices and concurrency load.
Regression scenarios (TC20, TC21) covered for old-default clearing and behavior when no payment methods exist.
Edge cases / parameter coverage (TC14, TC18, TC19, TC24, TC25) including extra query parameters, slow dependencies, injection attempts, empty pluginProperty array, and accessibility considerations.
gaps: Pagination: Not applicable for PUT in this story; no tests around listing or pagination were required by the story or guidelines.
Rate Limiting: No tests specifically verify rate limiting or throttling under high load.
Caching Behavior: No tests around caching headers (ETag, Cache-Control) or related caching behavior.
Partial Update validation: PUT typically implies full update; explicit tests ensuring partial updates are rejected (if applicable) are not present.
Duplicate Submissions: No explicit test ensuring idempotency or handling of duplicate submissions.
Large payloads: No explicit test cases sending very large payloads to exercise server handling.
Minimum/Maximum headers besides required ones: While some header coverage exists (TC04), further exhaustive testing of header edge cases is not explicit.
Accessibility (TC25) is included, but deeper accessibility checks of error bodies and API docs could be more comprehensive.
recommendations: Add rate limiting tests to ensure the system handles bursts of requests (e.g., >N requests per second).
Introduce caching header validation tests if caching is expected for this PUT path (e.g., ETag/Cache-Control presence or absence).
Add explicit idempotency/duplicate-submission tests to confirm PUT is idempotent or define behavior on repeated calls.
Add partial-update validation tests to confirm PUT does not accept or incorrectly handles partial payloads where not allowed (align with API contract).
Consider large-payload/end-to-end performance tests (stress load) to validate behavior under very large pluginProperty arrays or payload sizes.
Enhance coverage for boundary and negative headers: additional tests around invalid or missing authentication tokens, unusual header values, and header injection risks beyond TC19.
Review TC16 to ensure min/max UUID boundary cases are clearly validated against real system constraints (existence vs format) and document expected results for each boundary.
